##Email from Kevin on 20140324 explaining the breakdown of "array gene groupings 03 31 2014.xlsx" -- logged here for consistency 

~~~
#From: Kevin Olivieri <kolivieri@sanfordburnham.org>
#Subj: "Gene groupings for HiNT data sets"

Hi Michael,

Its kind of a long message here, but I wanted to try to tell you in as much detail as I could what and why I was sending you. If you want to just start trying out the data before reading all below, feel free. Well, here it goes:

I put together some sets of genes for you to try out in your analysis. I have asked for help from others, particularly to map the genes to all known pathways, but that is in progress. What I have done is grouped the genes by how they have fared in our HiNT related assays and in pathways related to innate immunity. On the first tab, you will see much of the same data I sent you last time with the mass spec determined HIV interactions and the results of our siRNA screen of that data set. After that are the genes that fell into significant complexes, determined by a network diffusion method. After that I listed three broad summary categories:  Immune Signaling, Abundance Change, and Virion Incorporation. The numbers in each row represent the number of studies the gene was found int. The tabs following have each of these broad summary categories broken down into their constituent data sets.

I chose these three categories for the following reasons. Immune signaling is an important category to consider because it may represent genes that help to counter viral replication or it may include genes that create an inflammatory condition in which HIV replicates more efficiently. Protein abundance change may reflect the degradation of cellular antiviral proteins by the virus. Lastly, I included a category that includes proteins that have been found in virions. These may be cellular proteins that are important for viral replication or are part of a system the virus needs to overcome to bud.

There are 7 immune signaling pathways represented and one list of genes induced by type 1 interferons. There are two extremes listed and several in-betweens. I mean that the NFkB pathways most likely lead to an inflammatory state that promotes viral replication. At the other extreme is Type 1 IFN signaling which leads to upregulation of antiviral genes. The other pathways represented have a mix of both inflammatory and antiviral components. These pathways I consider between the two extremes of antiviral or proviral signaling.

Protein abundance changes were estimated in 5 different assays. Vpu mediated degradation of Interferon stimulated genes was done to estimate how HIV may counter interferon-mediated restriction of  viral replication. The amount of ubiquitinated proteins underwent was estimated by mass spec. These proteins may include antiviral proteins that the virus degrades to overcome their negative influence on replication. Protein abundance was also measured after HIV infection in two different assays. One involved infection and the other involved induction from cells already harboring an HIV genome. When protein abundance is lost, that too may reflect the degradation of an antiviral protein by the virus. Lastly, there was a screen run to determine if the HIV protease directly degrades antiviral proteins within the cell.

Virion incorporation studies have been carried out by three different groups, each using different techniques. Each technique has its own strengths and weaknesses. Therefore, it was hard to rule out any one study. The proteins found in virions may be important for viral replication or are part of a system the virus needs to overcome to bud.

On all pages, I listed the HIV binding data and the results of our functional screen. I thought, as things went alone, perhaps you would be able to break down the above categories into functional or not, which just multiplies things by two. I guess that is not so bad. You may find it interesting to break down the gene groups, where large enough, by HIV interacting partner. There are 18, but I dont think there are many groups large enough for this analysis to cover each HIV  gene.

I know it is a lot of info, so be sure to let me know if you have any questions.

Best,

Kevin
